::::I didn't really have an opinion on the subject prior to this so I did some digging.
::::I looked at the earliest (available) version of the data of PS2s from Sony website, which dates from [https://web.archive.org/web/20230331170120/https://sonyinteractive.com/en/our-company/business-data-sales/ March 31st 2023].
::::It states, quote : '''''More than 155.0 million (As of March 31, 2012)'''''
::::It appears that as late as [https://web.archive.org/web/20241127005025/https://sonyinteractive.com/en/our-company/business-data-sales/ November 27th 2024] they were claiming that number, I find it very odd that a company, who claimed sales figure up to 2012 (over a decade prior to them "correcting" their numbers) and haven't had the console manufactured since January 2013.
::::I also want to insert this piece of information [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PlayStation_2#Later_years_and_discontinuation from the Wikipedia article on the PS2]:
::::"In February 2024, Jim Ryan (CEO of Sony Interactive Entertainment) confirmed on the Official PlayStation Podcast that the PlayStation 2 had sold 160 million units worldwide. This statement was not directly corroborated by Sony themselves until eight months later, when this figure officially appeared on the PlayStation 30th Anniversary website in November that year."
::::Does it really take them an entire decade to assess an extra 5 million units sold? For the (apparently) best selling console of all time, by one of the biggest consumer electronics (let alone video games) companies in the world? It does seem very sketchy.
::::I vote for re-establishing 155 million as the correct number, but I won't contribute to an edit war over this. [[User:HenriDeadMort|HenriDeadMort]] ([[User talk:HenriDeadMort|talk]]) 23:57, 8 February 2026 (UTC)

=== Eiffel Tower ===
In 2026, Germain was announced as one of 72 historical women in STEM whose names have been proposed to be added to the [[List of the 72 names on the Eiffel Tower|72 men]] already celebrated on the [[Eiffel Tower]]. The plan was announced by the Mayor of Paris, [[Anne Hidalgo]] following the recommendations of a committee led by Isabelle Vauglin of ''Femmes et Sciences'' and Jean-François Martins of the operating company which runs the Eiffel Tower.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Campbell, Paul J; Grinstein, Louise S |url=http://archive.org/details/womenofmathemati0000unse |title=Women of mathematics : a biobibliographic sourcebook |date=1987 |publisher=New York : Greenwood Press |others=Internet Archive |isbn=978-0-313-24849-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Eiffel Tower: a list of 72 women scientists will soon be inscribed on the Parisian monument |url=https://www.sortiraparis.com/en/news/in-paris/articles/340564-eiffel-tower-list-of-72-women-scientists-soon-to-be-honored-on-the-paris-landmark |access-date=2026-02-05 |website=www.sortiraparis.com |language=en}}</ref> Germain's work on the theory of elasticity underlaid the calculations used in the construction of the tower but her name was not included in the original list of scientists.{{sfn|Gray|1978}}
In 2026, Germain was announced as one of 72 historical women in STEM whose names have been proposed to be added to the [[List of the 72 names on the Eiffel Tower|72 men]] already celebrated on the [[Eiffel Tower]]. The plan was announced by the Mayor of Paris, [[Anne Hidalgo]] following the recommendations of a committee led by Isabelle Vauglin of ''Femmes et Sciences'' and Jean-François Martins of the operating company which runs the Eiffel Tower.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Campbell, Paul J; Grinstein, Louise S |url=http://archive.org/details/womenofmathemati0000unse |title=Women of mathematics : a biobibliographic sourcebook |date=1987 |publisher=New York : Greenwood Press |others=Internet Archive |isbn=978-0-313-24849-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Eiffel Tower: a list of 72 women scientists will soon be inscribed on the Parisian monument |url=https://www.sortiraparis.com/en/news/in-paris/articles/340564-eiffel-tower-list-of-72-women-scientists-soon-to-be-honored-on-the-paris-landmark |access-date=2026-02-05 |website=www.sortiraparis.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Les noms des 72 femmes pour la Tour Eiffel ont été révélés. |url=https://www.femmesetsciences.fr/news/les-noms-des-72-femmes-pour-la-tour-eiffel-ont-%C3%A9t%C3%A9-r%C3%A9v%C3%A9l%C3%A9 |access-date=2026-02-08 |website=Femmes & Sciences |language=fr}}</ref><ref>[https://10ca8303-b3dc-4a91-9dcc-2d2b91792b47.usrfiles.com/ugd/10ca83_3838bd19a41a4e83927cfc8fe0f50404.pdf 72 femmes de sciences pour la tour Eiffel] ''Femmes & Sciences'' (in French). During the 1960s and 1970s, while owned by Washington DC–based Rau Radio, WARK was a primary source for top 40 music in Hagerstown. Around 1977, WARK adjusted its format to "Adult Rock" (an early form of the "adult contemporary" format) and took on the 15ARK moniker. This lasted until February 1981, when they became Skyline Radio, a mixed talk/music format.
